## Thread.Abort Migration to .NET 8

### Pattern Analysis

Your code has **4 patterns** that need migration:

| Location | Pattern | Replacement |
|----------|---------|-------------|
| `Stop()` → `Thread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `ProcessLoop()` → `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Exception as control flow | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `ProcessLoop()` → `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |
| `GetNextItem()` — "may block" | Blocking call interruption | Pass token to unblock |

### Why This Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — the runtime **cannot** forcibly terminate a thread. Your `Stop()` method will crash, and the worker thread will never stop if `GetNextItem()` is blocked.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — migrated from ThreadAbortException handler
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — we control the loop via the token.
                // Loop condition will exit naturally.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait with a timeout instead of Thread.Sleep + Abort
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));

        _cts.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

---

### Critical: You Must Update `GetNextItem`

The original comment says `GetNextItem()` "may block." If it blocks indefinitely, cancellation **stalls** because cooperative cancellation only works if the code checks the token. You must pass the token through:

```csharp
// If it uses a BlockingCollection<T>:
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException on cancel
}

// If it uses Thread.Sleep or polling:
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    while (!_dataAvailable)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(100);        // replaces Thread.Sleep
    }
    return DequeueItem();
}

// If it calls synchronous I/O you can't modify (e.g., 3rd-party):
// Move to a child process and use Process.Kill as last resort.
```

---

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | What happens |
|---------|-------------|
| **Not passing token to `GetNextItem`** | Thread hangs forever — `Cancel()` has no effect on a blocking call that doesn't check the token |
| **Not passing token through `ProcessItem` either** | If `ProcessItem` is long-running, cancellation is delayed until it finishes |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers and registered callbacks |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` without the `when` filter** | Could swallow unrelated cancellations from inner operations |
| **Assuming `Cancel()` is instant** | Cancellation only fires at the next checkpoint (`ThrowIfCancellationRequested`, `WaitOne`, `Take`, etc.) |

### What Changed and Why

| Old (.NET Framework) | New (.NET 8) | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs; a bool cannot wake a blocked thread |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | `Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8 |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | `OperationCanceledException` is the cooperative equivalent |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed — not needed | Loop condition (`!token.IsCancellationRequested`) controls continuation |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` then Abort | `_workerThread.Join(2s)` | Waits for graceful exit; no forced termination needed |
